%N A396266 Area of the smallest simple polygon (by area) which can be triangulated into n different primitive Pythagorean triangles.
%C A396266 Here polygons are strictly simple, such that all vertices lie on the perimeter of the polygon, no vertex touches more than 2 line segments on the perimeter (as in a degenerate simple polygon, with a fold or enclosing a hole), and no vertex is in the middle of a straightaway.
%C A396266 Variations of this sequence that relax some or all of these conditions still produce many of the same terms, including all terms up to and including n = 26. For n = 27, the area of the smallest self-intersecting polygon that can be constructed from 27 different primitive Pythagorean triangles adjoined at equal length edges is 1560138, which is smaller than a(27) (1676502).
%C A396266 For most polygons, the smallest constituent triangle is 3,4,5; n = 6 is the only known exception, with 8,15,17 as its smallest triangle. It is unknown if this is the only such case.
%H A396266 Charles L. Hohn, <a href="/A396266/a396266.pdf">Example illustration of a(34)</a>
%H A396266 Charles L. Hohn, <a href="/A396266/a396266.txt">PARI function for generating A396266 and related sequences</a>, 2026.
%e A396266 a(1) = 6: a 3,4,5 triangle.
%e A396266 a(2) = 36: a 3,4,5 and a 5,12,13 triangle adjoined at their sides of length 5, in any orientation.
%e A396266 a(3) = 246: 3,4,5, 5,12,13, and 12,35,37, in any orientation.
